<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-495-814  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 495 814.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  May 21 1990 v4 n20 p19(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Optical storage technology.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rivenbark, Leigh.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Federal agencies must protect investments in existing equipmentand cannot quickly change as new technologies come along.andP;  Butgovernment agencies are the target audience for new opticalstorage technology.andP;  The new technology includes dual-head drivescapable of reading both sides of a disk simultaneously, opticaldisk jukeboxes that are small enough to place on the desktop orsmart enough to rearrange frequently used disks, multifunctiondrives capable of using both write-once and rewritable mediainterchangeably and optical tape, a high-density storage medium.andO;There is strong interest in the 5.25-inch disk because of its lowcost.andP;  Two areas of optical storage frequently overlooked but ofprime importance to federal agencies are the increasing importanceof service bureaus to convert huge quantities of documents tooptical storage and the emergence of affordable computer outputmicrofilm devices.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government AgencyNational GovernmentOptical DisksTrends.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Optical disk drives: worldwide installed base/year-end 1989.andO;(table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>